	": We don't use an official definition of a "cheat" and we don't try to decide whether something is a cheat or not (normally). We use 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext="in-game code"|href=/Glossary#CodeModification)
	", and cheats in this game don't really look like those. You collect them like items and they're enabled by default, so it's easy to conclude they're a part of normal gameplay: you have to disable them through the menu to actually play without them. And they don't require passing any "codes" to the game.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"It's perfectly fine to avoid using certain in-game mechanics, it'd just result in the movie going to a non-standard class (Alternative in this case). It's perfectly clear which type of mechanic we're avoiding, and it makes gameplay really different. And a movie that uses those "cheats" to their full potential would go to the standard class with the "full completion" tag (and "107%" label).
	$LF
]div
